'''Darcy G. Richardson''' (born December 6, 1955) is an American [[author]], [[historian]] and [[political activist]].

He was the [[Reform Party of Florida]]'s nominee for governor in [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]. In the [[U.S. presidential election, 2012|2012 presidential election]], Richardson challenged incumbent [[Barack Obama]] for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination for [[president of the United States]] in five state primaries.

==Author and activist==
Richardson is the author of ''A Nation Divided: The 1968 Presidential Campaign'', published in 2002. The book describes in detail the "Clean for Gene" phenomenon that led to President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s startling withdrawal from the race and [[Robert F. Kennedy]]'s resulting candidacy, as well as the campaigns of Republican [[Richard M. Nixon]] and others. He has also authored four books of a planned seven volume series on the history of third party politics in the United States, with a heavy focus on progressive movements. The first volume, "Others: Third-Party Politics From the Nation's Founding to the Rise and Fall of the Greenback-Labor Party" earned a ''[[Choice: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries|Choice magazine]]'' Outstanding Academic Title (OAT) award for 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ala.org/awardsgrants/awards/370/winners/2005?page=54 | title=ALA Outstanding Academic Titles | work=American Library Association | accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref>

Richardson has contributed articles to numerous publications and is the co-founder of a blog called Uncovered Politics, which focuses on insurgent candidates and third party politics.

Between 1989 and 1992, Richardson served as the National Chairman of The New Democrats, a Progressive reformist group that included [[Eugene McCarthy]] and [[Gary Hart]].<ref name="phil 1989">
{{Cite news
  | last = Herman
  | first = Steven L.
  | title = The "New Democrats" are Liberals and Proud of It
  | newspaper = Associated Press
  | date=December 4, 1989}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tdNRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZW4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6685,4032628&dq=darcy-richardson+new+democrats&hl=en | title=Small uprising developing among national Democrats | work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] | date=December 13, 1989 | accessdate=November 4, 2011 | author=Stack, Barbara White}}</ref>

==Political campaigns==
Although a registered Democrat and elected [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]] precinct committeeman at the time, Richardson was nominated to run for the position of Pennsylvania Auditor General in 1980 on the [[Philadelphia]]-based Consumer Party's ballot line. In that race he finished third with 48,783 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=611002|title=Our Campaigns - PA Auditor Race - Nov 04, 1980|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>

In 1988, the [[Citizens Party (United States)|Consumer Party]] again nominated Richardson, this time to run for [[U.S. Senate]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2stRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3W0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3824,2604379&dq=darcy-richardson&hl=en | title=Heinz well on road to win | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=November 9, 1988 | accessdate=November 4, 2011}}</ref> That same year, Richardson was the national campaign manager of former Senator [[Eugene McCarthy]]'s presidential campaign. McCarthy was also running on the Consumer Party ticket. Richardson was later a senior advisor to McCarthy's final presidential campaign, in which he ran as a candidate in the 1992 Democratic primaries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.battlegroundblog.com/about|title=BattlegroundBlog.com About Page|publisher=|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>

Richardson was a candidate for the lieutenant governor of [[Florida]] in 2010, running with [[Independent (politician)|independent]] gubernatorial candidate [[Farid Khavari]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theledger.com/article/20101003/COLUMNISTS/10035055D | title=Write-ins and Independents Fill Out Ballot | work=The Ledger of LAKELAND | date=October 3, 2010 | accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>

===2012 presidential campaign===
{{Wikinews|Wikinews interviews Darcy Richardson, Democratic Party presidential challenger to Barack Obama}}
[[File:Second-place candidates in the Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2012.svg|thumb|Map of second-place candidates in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2012|2012 Democratic presidential primaries]]<br>'''Legend:'''<br>
{{legend|#FF8C00 |[[Keith Russell Judd]]}}
{{legend|#FF0000|[[Ron Paul]]}}
{{legend|#00FFFF |Darcy Richardson}}
{{legend|#800080 |[[John Wolfe Jr.]]}}
{{legend|#800000 |[[Randall Terry]]}}
{{legend|#808080|Uncommitted/other}}
{{legend|#000000|No second-place finisher}}
{{legend|#D3D3D3|No primary held/ no info available}}]]

On October 21, 2011, Richardson filed as a candidate in the [[New Hampshire Democratic primary, 2012|2012 New Hampshire Democratic primary]] and became the first Democrat to file in a primary against President Barack Obama.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ballot-access.org/2011/10/21/darcy-richardson-files-in-new-hampshire-democratic-presidential-primary/ | title=Darcy Richardson Files in New Hampshire Democratic Presidential Primary | work=[[Ballot Access News]] | date=October 21, 2011 | accessdate=November 3, 2011 | author=[[Richard Winger|Winger, Richard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boston.com/Boston/politicalintelligence/2011/10/primary-ballot-becomes-equalizer-between-top-tier-perennial-candidates/MkD7dWcT2Nq0gUe2Gv1GuM/index.html | title=N.H. primary ballot becomes equalizer between top-tier, perennial candidates | work=[[Boston Globe]] | date=October 28, 2011 | accessdate=November 4, 2011 | author=Schoenberg, Shira}}</ref> A total of 14 Democrats, including Obama, eventually filed for the primary ballot.<ref name="crowded">{{cite web | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-new-hampshire-candidates-20111028,0,7479283.story | title=Even Democratic ballot will be crowded in New Hampshire primary | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=October 28, 2011 | accessdate=November 4, 2011 | author=Memoli, Michael A.}}</ref> Richardson stated in an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that he decided to enter the race after failing to convince former Labor Secretary [[Robert Reich]] to mount a bid. Richardson also noted his campaign was to be national in scope, with plans to file in numerous other states where ballot access laws would allow him to either pay a qualifying fee or gather signed petitions.<ref name=crowded/> In addition to New Hampshire, he qualified for a spot on the Missouri, Louisiana, Oklahoma, and Texas Democratic primary ballots,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therepublic.com/view/story/28c515b299cd4acf8c613b671bbf1cdd/LA--Presidential-Primary/ |title=Associated Press |date=December 7, 2011 |accessdate=December 7, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ppp_filing.html | title=Oklahoma Board of Elections | date=December 8, 2011 | accessdate=December 8, 2011}}</ref> and accumulated 41,730 votes at the end of the primary season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/P12/D | title=The Green Papers | date=July 15, 2012 | accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>

In April 2012, Richardson suspended his presidential campaign,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Darcy_Richardson_suspends_Democratic_Party_presidential_campaign?dpl_id=425312 | title=Darcy Richardson suspends Democratic Party presidential campaign | work=[[Wikinews]] | date=April 28, 2012 | accessdate=May 13, 2012}}</ref> and announced plans to support [[Reform Party of the United States of America|Reform Party]] presidential candidate and former Louisiana governor [[Buddy Roemer]] in the general election.<ref name="wn">{{cite web|url=http://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Darcy_Richardson_to_seek_Reform_Party_presidential_nomination|title=Darcy Richardson to seek Reform Party presidential nomination|date=June 15, 2012|work=[[Wikinews]]|accessdate=June 19, 2012}}</ref> After Roemer ended his campaign, Richardson backed [[Roseanne Barr]]'s presidential campaign and organized a Florida chapter of the [[Peace and Freedom Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentpoliticalreport.com/2012/08/darcy-richardson-comments-on-reform-national-convention-2012-endorsement/|title=Darcy Richardson Comments on Reform National Convention & 2012 Endorsement|date=16 August 2012|publisher=|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>

===2018 gubenatorial campaign===
On June 22, 2018, Richardson became the [[Reform Party of Florida]]'s nominee [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2018|for governor]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/darcy-richardson-opts-run-governor-reform-party-line|title=Darcy Richardson Opts to Run for Governor on Reform Party Line|date=8 June 2018|publisher=|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> later choosing [[Nancy Argenziano]] as his running mate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/nancy-argenziano-joins-darcy-richardson-reform-party-gubernatorial-ticket|title=Nancy Argenziano Joins Darcy Richardson on Reform Party Gubernatorial Ticket|date=30 August 2018|publisher=|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>

