{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}} {{for|the Australian rules footballer|Greg Stafford (footballer)}} {{Infobox person |name = Greg Stafford |image = Image:Greg Stafford.jpg |image_size = |caption = Greg Stafford in [[Helsinki, Finland]] on July 21, 2005 |birth_name = Francis Gregory Stafford |birth_date = {{Birth date|1948|2|9}} |birth_place = [[Waterbury, Connecticut]], U.S.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120419143141/http://www.weareallus.com/biography/eventsofmylife.html Greg Stafford's biographical timeline], by himself on his personal website (archived)</ref> |death_date = {{death date and age|2018|10|11|1948|2|9}} |death_place = [[Arcata, California]], U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chaosium.com/blogvale-greg-stafford-1948-2018/|title=Vale Greg Stafford (1948 - 2018)|author=Michael O'Brien|website=Chaosium company blog|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 12, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012165915/https://www.chaosium.com/blogvale-greg-stafford-1948-2018/|archivedate=October 12, 2018|deadurl=no}}</ref> |spouse = |nationality = [[Americans|American]] |residence = |other_names = |known_for = |education = |employer = |occupation = [[Game designer]] |home_town = |website = }}
'''Francis Gregory Stafford''' (February 9, 1948 – October 11, 2018), usually known as '''Greg Stafford''', was an [[Americans|American]] [[game designer]], [[publisher]], and practitioner of [[shamanism]].
Stafford is most famous as the creator of the fantasy world of [[Glorantha]], but he is also a prolific games designer. He was designer of ''[[Pendragon RPG|Pendragon]]'', he was co-designer of the ''[[RuneQuest]]'', Ghostbusters, Prince Valiant and ''[[HeroQuest (role-playing game)|HeroQuest]]'' [[role-playing game system|role-playing systems]], founder of the role-playing game companies [[Chaosium]] and [[Issaries, Inc.|Issaries]], designer of the ''[[White Bear and Red Moon]]'', ''[[Nomad Gods]]'', ''King Arthur’s Knights'' and ''Elric'' [[board game]]s, and co-designer of the ''[[King of Dragon Pass]]'' [[computer game]].
==Gaming industry career== ===1970s–: Chaosium === Greg Stafford began wargaming after picking up a copy of ''U-Boat'' by [[Avalon Hill]], and in 1966 as a freshman at [[Beloit College]] he started writing about the fantasy world of [[Glorantha]].<ref name="designers">{{Cite book|author=Shannon Appelcline|title=Designers & Dragons: A History of the Roleplaying Game Industry|publisher=Mongoose Publishing|year=2011| isbn= 978-1-907702-58-7}}</ref>{{rp|82}} After rejection from a publisher, Stafford created ''[[White Bear and Red Moon]]'' set in Glorantha, and after three different companies were unable to publish the game he created [[Chaosium]].<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|82}} He derived the name partly from his home, which was near the [[Oakland Coliseum]], and combining "coliseum" with "chaos."<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|82}}
''White Bear and Red Moon'' (1975) was Chaosium's first published game,<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|82}} and was also Stafford's first professional game.<ref name="HG">{{Cite book | contribution=[[Kingmaker (board game)|Kingmaker]] | title=Hobby Games: The 100 Best | last=Stafford | first=Greg | authorlink= | editor-last=Lowder | editor-first=James | editor-link=James Lowder | publisher=[[Green Ronin Publishing]] | year=2007 | pages=164–167 | isbn=978-1-932442-96-0}}</ref> Stafford designed the board game ''[[Nomad Gods]]''.<ref name="HG"/> Stafford also designed the wargames ''[[Elric: Battle at the End of Time|Elric]]'' (1977) and ''King Arthur's Knights'' (1978).<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|82}}
Stafford wanted the world of Glorantha to be part of an original role-playing game; this ultimately resulted in [[Steve Perrin]]'s ''[[RuneQuest]]'' (1978), which was set in Glorantha.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|83}}
Stafford and [[Lynn Willis]] simplified the ''RuneQuest'' rules into the 16-page ''[[Basic Role-Playing]]'' (1980).<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|85}} He designed the miniatures game ''Merlin''.<ref name="HG"/> Stafford considers his [[Arthurian]] [[chivalric]] role-playing game ''[[Pendragon (role-playing game)|King Arthur Pendragon]]'' (1985) his masterpiece.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|88}}<ref name="Phantasie">[http://weltentore.dyndns.org/?Interviews:Greg_Stafford:English_Version Interview with Greg Stafford] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719194323/http://weltentore.dyndns.org/?Interviews:Greg_Stafford:English_Version |date=2009-07-19 }} on ''Phantasie'' website. URL checked 2008-02-13.</ref> He co-designed the ''[[Ghostbusters (role-playing game)|Ghostbusters]]'' role-playing game (1986).<ref name="HG"/>
Stafford designed the ''[[Prince Valiant: The Story-Telling Game|Prince Valiant]]'' roleplaying game (1989), which featured a strong storytelling basis and other innovations.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|90}} Stafford decided to produce a fiction line for ''[[Call of Cthulhu (role-playing game)|Call of Cthulhu]]'' after he realized that many [[H. P. Lovecraft|Lovecraft]] fans of the early 1990s had never actually read Lovecraft's fiction but were only familiar with him through ''Call of Cthulhu''.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|91}} Stafford co-designed the computer game ''[[King of Dragon Pass]]'' (1999).<ref name="HG"/>
===1998–: Issaries === Stafford left Chaosium in 1998, taking all of the rights for Glorantha, and founded the game company [[Issaries, Inc.|Issaries]].<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|94}}
Stafford approached [[Robin Laws]] to create a new game based on Glorantha, which became known as ''[[Hero Wars]]'', published in 2000 as the first fully professional product for Issaries.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|361}} Stafford published the second edition in 2003 under the name he always wanted ''[[HeroQuest (role-playing game)|HeroQuest]]'', as Milton Bradley's trademark on the name had lapsed.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|362}} Stafford moved to Mexico in 2004, bringing production from Issaries to an end.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|363}}
===Later years=== When Hasbro let the ''RuneQuest'' trademark lapse, Stafford picked up the rights to the game and licensed [[Mongoose Publishing]] to publish a new edition in 2006.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|363}} After [[White Wolf Publishing|White Wolf]] acquired the rights to ''[[Pendragon RPG|''Pendragon'']]'', it was republished in 2005 by White Wolf. Their ArtHaus imprint published ''The Great Pendragon Campaign'' (2006), in which Stafford detailed the massive RPG campaign from the years 485 to 566.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|228}} After Nocturnal Games picked up the rights to ''Pendragon'', Stafford created a 5.1 edition of ''Pendragon'' (2010).<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|230}}
He moved from [[Berkeley, California]] to [[Arcata, California]] in 2007, having lived in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] for some years.<ref>{{Cita web|url=http://www.staffordcodex.com/about-me/|title=About me|author=Greg Stafford|website=staffordcodex.com/|accessdate=2018-10-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013082318/http://www.staffordcodex.com/about-me/|archivedate=2018-10-13}}</ref>
In June 2015, it was announced that Greg and [[Sandy Petersen]] had returned to Chaosium Inc., Stafford taking the positions of President and CEO.<ref>{{cite web|title=GREG STAFFORD & SANDY PETERSEN REJOIN CHAOSIUM INC.|url=http://www.chaosium.com/blog/greg-stafford-sandy-petersen-rejoin-chaosium-inc/|date=2015-06-02|accessdate=2015-06-03|first=Greg|last=Stafford}}</ref>
==Glorantha== {{main|Glorantha}} {{refimprove-section|date=October 2018}} Greg Stafford's interest in roleplaying and gaming originated in his adolescent fascination with [[mythology]]. During his adolescent years he read anything he could find on the subject, and when he exhausted the libraries, he started to write his own stories in his freshman year at [[Beloit College]], in 1966. This was the start of the world of Glorantha.
Stafford's 1974 board game ''White Bear and Red Moon'' had featured the violent struggle between several cultures in the Dragon Pass region of Glorantha. The heart of the game was a conflict between the [[barbarian]] Kingdom of Sartar and the invading Lunar Empire, a theme which has remained central to Gloranthan publications since then.
As Stafford was founding his company Chaosium, the game ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'' (and the concept of [[tabletop role-playing game]]s) was gaining great popularity. Role-players were keen to use the ''White Bear and Red Moon'' setting in such games. So Chaosium published ''[[RuneQuest]]'', written by "[[Steve Perrin]], Ray Turney, and Friends". Stafford left Chaosium in 1998.
For some years, Stafford slowly wrote several [[novel]]s set in Glorantha. Novels that he is known to have been working on are ''Harmast's Saga'', ''Arkat's Saga'', and his "Lunar novel".
He was one of the designers on the Glorantha-based video game "''[[King of Dragon Pass]]''".<ref name="RPGnet review">[http://www.rpg.net/news+reviews/reviews/rev_2592.html Review of King of Dragon Pass, rpg.net] URL checked 2011-01-14.</ref>
==Shamanism-related works==
Stafford was a practicing shaman and member of the board of directors of ''[[Shaman's Drum]]'', a journal of experiential shamanism.{{cn|date=October 2018}} He had some short articles of Arthurian interest published.{{cn|date=October 2018}} Stafford lived in [[Mexico]] for 18 months, tutoring English as a foreign language, and exploring places of archeological and shamanic interest.{{cn|date=October 2018}}
==Honors and reception== Fantasy author [[David A. Hargrave]] pays homage to Stafford in the [[Arduin]] series of supplements, the most widely known example of this being the [[Arduin#Greg Stafford and Chaosium|Stafford's Star Bridge]] 9th-Level [[wizard (character class)|mage]] spell ([[Arduin]] I, page 41).{{cn|date=October 2018}}
Stafford was inducted in the [[Origins Award]] hall of fame in 1987<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.originsawards.net/hall-of-fame/|title=Hall of Fame|work=The Academy of Adventure Gaming Arts & Design|accessdate=2018-10-17}}</ref>.
In 1999 ''[[Pyramid (magazine)|Pyramid]]'' magazine named Greg Stafford one of The Millennium's Most Influential Persons, "at least in the realm of adventure gaming."<ref>{{cite journal|title=Second Sight: The Millennium's Best "Other" Game and The Millennium's Most Influential Person|journal=[[Pyramid (magazine)|Pyramid]] (online)|url=http://www.sjgames.com/pyramid/login/article.html?id=1306|last=Haring|first=Scott D.|date=1999-12-24|accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref>
Stafford won the [[Diana Jones Award]] in 2007, for ''The Great Pendragon Campaign'', published by [[White Wolf Publishing|White Wolf]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dianajonesaward.org/the-2007-award/|title=The 2007 Award|website=The Diana Jones Award for Excellence in Gamig|accessdate=2018-10-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411075745/http://www.dianajonesaward.org/the-2007-award/|archivedate=2018-04-11|deadurl=no}}</ref> and in 2015 for ''Guide to Glorantha'', coauthored with Jeff Richard and [[Sandy Petersen]] and published by [[Moon Design Publications]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dianajonesaward.org/the-2015-award/|title=The 2015 Award|website=The Diana Jones Award for Excellence in Gamig|accessdate=2018-10-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323131234/http://www.dianajonesaward.org:80/the-2015-award/|archivedate=2018-03-23|deadurl=no}}</ref>
He was honored as a "famous game designer" by being featured as the king of hearts in [[Flying Buffalo]]'s 2011 Famous Game Designers Playing Card Deck.<ref name="buffalo_dec">{{cite web| url=http://www.flyingbuffalo.com/pokerdeck.htm| title=Poker Deck| publisher=Flying Buffalo| accessdate=February 11, 2014}}</ref>
