{{Infobox person |image = Replace_this_image_male.svg <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people. See [[WP:NONFREE]]. --> |image_size = 150px | |name = Nikita Borisov |caption = |birth_date = 24 December 1977 |birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union|USSR]] |residence = [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]] |known_for = [[Off-the-Record Messaging|OTR]] |occupation = [[Professor]], [[UIUC]] |website = http://hatswitch.org/~nikita/ }}
'''Nikita Borisov''' is a cryptographer and [[computer security]] researcher, currently an associate professor at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]] (UIUC). His notable work includes one of the first [[cryptanalysis|cryptanalyses]] of the [[Wired Equivalent Privacy|WEP]] wireless encryption protocol together with [[Ian Goldberg]] and [[David A. Wagner|David Wagner]], and the design of the [[Off-the-Record Messaging]] protocol with Goldberg.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jorn|last=Barger|authorlink=Jorn Barger|title= Paradigms for Paranoids: Off-the-record messaging|url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/02/14/codecon_paradigm_for_paranoids/|work= [[The Register]]|date=February 14, 2005|accessdate=April 23, 2009}}</ref>
Borisov received a [[BMath|B. Math]] in [[computer science]] and [[pure math]] in 1997 from the [[University of Waterloo]]. He received an [[M.S.]] and a [[Ph.D.]] in [[computer science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 2002 and 2005, respectively.
Borisov is an avid runner and completed the [[Illinois Marathon]] in April 2018.
