'''Raymond Gniewek ''' (born November 13, 1931 in East Meadow, New York <ref name="wedding"/>) is an [[United States|American]] violinist. He served as [[concertmaster]] of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] orchestra for 43 years; upon his appointment in 1957 he was the youngest person to ever hold the post. He has also had a career as a soloist.<ref>[http://www.bso.org/bso/mods/bios_detail.jsp?id=41600158 Biography] at the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]]</ref> His final performance as concertmaster with the orchestra was a concert performance in Carnegie Hall of [[Béla Bartók]]'s ''[[Bluebeard's Castle]]'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=|title=MUSIC REVIEW; Thunder From the Pit For Bluebeard|author=[[Bernard Holland]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 23, 2000}}</ref> Gniewek is a native of [[New York City]], where he began his musical education; he continued at the [[Eastman School of Music]], studying with Andre de Ribaupierre and Joseph Knitzer, becoming concertmaster of the [[Eastman Rochester Orchestra]] and associate concertmaster of [[Rochester Philharmonic]] under [[Erich Leinsdorf]]. Other teachers were the Canadian violinist [[Albert Pratz]] and Raphael Bronstein of New York City.<ref name="CE">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/albert-pratz-emc/|title=Albert Pratz|author=[[Maud McLean]]|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>
Gniewek is currently married to soprano [[Judith Blegen]].<ref>[http://www.bso.org/bso/mods/bios_detail.jsp?id=41600158 "The Met's Judith Blegen and Ray Gniewek Are a Duet: She Sings, He Strings"] from ''People'' magazine, October 26, 1981</ref> He was formerly married to ballet dancer and Pilates instructor [[Lolita San Miguel]].<ref name="wedding">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4AQpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dkgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4863,5811104&dq=raymond-gniewek&hl=en|title=Stage Wedding Real Thing: another Metropolitan First|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=May 27, 1960}}</ref> His sister is Cecilia Brauer who plays [[celesta]] and [[glass harmonica]] in the Met Orchestra.<ref>[http://www.metorchestramusicians.org/cecilia-brauer/ "Cecilia Brauer, celeste," ''Met Orchestra Musicians'' (website, accessed April 27, 2016).]</ref>
