'''Theodor Szehinskyj''' (February 14, 1924 – 2014) was an alleged [[World War II]] [[war criminal]]. He was born in [[Mallnow, Poland]]. He was a member of an SS Totenkopf Battalion and is accused of having been a guard in three [[concentration camp]]s in [[Germany]], [[Poland]] and [[Ukraine]]. Szehinskyj emigrated to the United States after the war, but was named as a war criminal by the United States Department of Justice in 2000, subsequently had his citizenship revoked, and is facing attempts to deport him from the country.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-08-27/news/41459421_1_nazi-war-crimes-theodor-szehinskyj-accused-nazi |title=Accused Nazi still has Chesco address |first=Aubrey |last=Whelan |date=August 27, 2013 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]}}</ref> He is on the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]'s [[List of Most Wanted Nazi War Criminals according to the Simon Wiesenthal Center|list of most wanted Nazi war criminals]].
The Szehinskyj family were Ukrainians resident in Poland. Fluent in both [[Polish language|Polish]] and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], he grew up on his parents' farm in Mallnow and worked there after completing seven grades of school. After the [[Occupation of Poland (1939–45)|Soviets occupied]] Mallnow during World War II and collectivized agriculture, he left his farm and moved to [[Lvov]], where he was captured by the Germans in early 1942. He was transported to Vienna and worked intermittently on a farm in Austria. From 1943 to early 1945 he allegedly served in the Waffen-SS belonging SS [[Totenkopf Division]] in the concentration camps of [[Gross-Rosen]], [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] and Warsaw. He was allegedly involved in the transport of prisoners from the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] in [[Mauthausen]] concentration camp shortly before the war ended in 1945. In 1950 Szehinskyj emigrated with his wife and daughter to the United States and worked as a machinist for [[General Electric]]. His US citizenship was revoked in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judge revokes citizenship of accused Nazi guard {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency|url=https://www.jta.org/2000/07/30/life-religion/features/judge-revokes-citizenship-of-accused-nazi-guard|website=www.jta.org|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He was ordered deported in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|title=Alleged Nazi Guard Is Ordered Deported|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/apr/21/nation/na-briefs21.2|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=5 April 2018|date=21 April 2003}}</ref> but remained in the United States until his death in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inside the race to deport a 94-year-old Nazi guard|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2017/12/16/nazi-guard-deportation/|website=The Denver Post|accessdate=5 April 2018|date=17 December 2017}}</ref>
